Agent object

An agent is a plain object with a stable ID (user-facing slug, not an address), a blueprint label, dynamic capabilities, a connections map, group memberships, a policy block, and storage references. Addresses live in the connections map and change freely.

{
  id: "alice-home",              // stable user slug
  blueprint: "household-agent", // named preset
  capabilities: {
    "summarise": {
      fn: <ref>,
      style: "request-response",
      visibility: "group:home",
      policy: "on-request"
    },
    "live-feed": {
      fn: <ref>,
      style: "streaming",
      visibility: "public",
      policy: "negotiated"
    }
  },
  connections: {
    nkn:  { address: "abc123.nkn" },
    mqtt: { broker: "mqtt://...", topic: "agents/alice-home" },
    mdns: { hostname: "alice-home.local" }   // native only
  },
  groups: [
    { id: "home", proof: "<signed-token>" }
  ],
  policy: {
    ping:       "always",
    messaging:  "on-request",
    streaming:  "negotiated",
    taskAccept: "negotiated"
  },
  storage: {
    cache:      "memory",
    persistent: "local-encrypted",
    sources: [
      { label: "private", type: "solid-pod", url: "https://..." },
      { label: "app",     type: "indexeddb", name: "myapp-db"  }
    ]
  },
  resources: {
    maxPendingTasks: 5,
    maxConnections: 20
  },
  hooks: {
    onTask:    ["log-to-email"],   // capability names
    onMessage: ["log-locally"]
  }
}

JSON portability

Calling agent.export() serialises this shape without runtime state, secrets, or resolved credentials. Agent.import(json) re-hydrates it. The format is the standard — any conforming runtime can load any conforming file.
Blueprint labels

A blueprint is a named, shareable preset of capabilities, policies, and hooks — not tied to a group or identity. Think of it as a role template: "drone-operator", "logger-agent". Apps can ship built-in blueprints; users can define their own in the agent file.